metadata.name: Alea iacta est 00001
metadata.description:
"Alea iacta est" is a Latin phrase attributed to Julius Caesar, meaning "The die is cast." It is said to have been spoken by Caesar as he crossed the Rubicon River with his army, signaling his intention to start a civil war against the Roman Republic. 

The phrase is often used to indicate that a decision has been made and that events are set in motion, with no turning back.
